    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I mean, you said it \"failed\" to establish stability, but some people argue that the instability was always going to happen because of the way the country was run before, regardless of the intervention. Is it fair to call the whole thing a failure if the actual military goal of protecting civilians was met, or is there a more \"correct\" way to measure if a foreign policy move worked?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This highlights the complex debate between immediate objectives and protracted consequences in foreign policy. Some argue that protection of civilians was the primary, and successful, mission metric. However, a comprehensive evaluation must account for secondary, unintended outcomes, like state failure, which constitute a major regional risk. Ultimately, success in intervention often requires a robust, long-term stabilization and reconstruction strategy, which was largely absent in 2011.",
      "source": "target",
